Vendored skills — attribution
==============================

Most core process skills under this directory are vendored (a curated, lightly
trimmed copy) from:

  superpowers — https://github.com/obra/superpowers
  Copyright (c) obra (Jesse Vincent) and contributors
  License: MIT

The obra/superpowers skills are redistributed under the terms of the MIT
License. The MIT permission notice is reproduced below. Only operational content
was kept; authoring/meta/test files and non–Claude-Code tool references were
removed. Skill methodology is unchanged.

Vendored skills from obra/superpowers:
  brainstorming, writing-plans, executing-plans, test-driven-development,
  systematic-debugging, verification-before-completion, requesting-code-review,
  receiving-code-review, dispatching-parallel-agents,
  subagent-driven-development, using-git-worktrees,
  finishing-a-development-branch, using-superpowers

Note on subagent-driven-development: this skill received a selective backport of
newer upstream additions (durable progress ledger, task-brief/review-package
scripts, explicit model-selection discipline, reviewer anti-pre-judging guidance)
on top of hero-mmt-kit's own Review Budget tiering system, which upstream does not
have. The backported additions remain obra/superpowers-origin content under MIT;
Review Budget tiering is a hero-mmt-kit original design choice.

Framework-authored skills shipped by hero-mmt-kit:
  security-review, using-hero, hero-planning, hero-coding, hero-reviewing,
  hero-unit-test, hero-security, hero-strict

Design / visual-direction skills are NOT vendored — they are referenced in
skills.manifest.json and installed from their original sources on demand.

Concise reporting principles in the hero-* workflow skills are inspired by the
compression-mode concept from:

  caveman — https://github.com/JuliusBrussee/caveman
  Copyright (c) Julius Brussee
  License: MIT

hero-mmt-kit no longer ships concise-output as a standalone skill. Its idea
(compress output, preserve technical accuracy, revert to full clarity for
safety-critical content) is integrated directly into using-hero and the hero-*
reporting guidance. No text was copied verbatim; only the underlying concept
was adapted. Reproduced below per MIT attribution practice.

